			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2009</a> paper:</span><br><i>Model Transformation Languages Relying on Models as ADTs</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/JerónimoIrazábal.html">Jerónimo Irazábal</a>, <a href="../profile/ClàudiaPons.html">Clàudia Pons</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_10">10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_10</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagM">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> It concerns the design/semantics of model transformation languages, using models as abstract data types.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> Treating models as ADTs implicates a metalanguage viewpoint for defining transformation languages.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> Using ADTs typically brings formal reasoning about correctness and properties of transformations.
</li></ul></li></ul>
